Section section_01 (Chars 0–8842):
Section Summary: Jean François Millet is a prominent painter of peasant life, and his work is characterized by incisive truth and absorbing sincerity. He is considered a direct descendant of the Dutch master Pieter Brueghel, who is now recognized as one of the greatest painters of his time. Millet's paintings, such as "The Angelus," convey the struggles and simple faith of rural life, and his use of subtle atmosphere and line requires an understanding of the countryside he depicted. Despite some criticism of sentimentality, Millet's work is infused with intense earnestness and melancholy truth, making it great and enduring art. Overall, Millet's unique style and approach to painting set him apart from his contemporaries, and his work continues to be appreciated for its profound and sympathetic rendering of peasant life.
